{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_minuette_ver01/data/sn87007277/00415662154/1910071501/0102.xml":{"full_text":"3?ll\nVOLXLV.\nLIBERTY, MISSISSIPPI, FRIDAY, JULY 15, 1910.\nNO. 14.\nACorner in Ancestors\nMil aTwWHN\nWW\n1TR\nWitt\nII J 1\n\"J\nill'\nPRESIDENT'S NEW SECRETARY\nCharles D. Norton, the new secretary to the\npresfuent bad been holding down the job of \"buf\nfer\" of the Taft administration only a few days\nuntil be \"butted\" Francis Burton Harrison, Demo\ncrat, and member of congress out of the White\nHouse In a huff.\nThe secretary to the president Is there to do\nJust that sort of thing and Mr. Norton did It with\nsuch ease that two other members of the Empire\nstate delegation who were present did not know\nthat Mr. Harrison bad been \"buffed.\"\nThe story of the clash between the president\nand the New York congressman Is not the sub\nject of discussion for this short sketch, but\nsuffice It to say that criticism by Mr. Harrison\nof the presidential action In connection with the\nBallluger-Plnchot row made the New York eon-\n1-essman persona non grata at the White House and Mr. Norton was the\nbe who told him so.\nMr. Norton only a short time ago succeeded Fred W. Camenter to the\nffice of secretary to the president He had been serving as an assistant\nsecretary of the treasury when President Taft selected him as the \"butter.\"\nMr. Norton Is in his fortieth year. He was born In Winnebago county,\nWis., at what is now Oshkosh, and la the son of the Rev. Franklin B. Nor\nton, a Congregational frontier missionary. From his early manhood until be\nbecame assistant secretary of the treasury last year he was Identified with\nthe Nothwestern Mutual Life Insurance company, first at the home office\nIn Milwaukee, later at Chicago in partnursblp with A. W. Kimball, becoming\nsole general agent there In 1905 upon Mr. Kimball's death. He has all the\nqualities of a good secretary.\nRIPLEY ACTIVE RAIL CHIEF\nEdward Payson Ripley, president of the Atchi\nson, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway company, Is\nabout the busiest railroad chief In this country.\nWhenever anything big la going on among the\nrailroads, especially those In the west, Mr. Rip\nley Is pretty sure to be found right In the front\nrank.\nRecently the western railroads considered It\nnecessary to Increase their freight rates and had\neverything ready to do so when President Taft\ntook a hand. As a result of presidential Inter\nference Judge Dyer of the United States district\ncourt Issued an Injunction restraining the roads\nfrom raising' the prices for whloh they would\nhaul freight.\nSeveral of the railroad chiefs, among them\nMr. Ripley, E. A. Delano, president of the Wa\nbash and 8. M. Felton, president of the Great Western met In Chicago. They\ndecided to take the matter up with the president personally at the White\nHouse and were received In conference with Mr. Taft. As a result of the\nmeeting It was agreed that the Injunction suit would be withdrawn and that\nthe roads would not attempt to Increase the rates.\nIt was not President Ripley's first important visit to the White House.\nHe was there more than once when the railroad rate bill was before congress\nand caused such a big fight The president of the Santa Fe had the confi\ndence of Theodore Roosevelt and he wielded his Influence In the Interests of\nthe stockholders of the Santa Fe.\nMr. Ripley was born in Dorchester, Mass., 65 years ago and after being\ngraduated from the high school there began railroad work as a clerk for\nthe Pennsylavnla Railroad company. His work was of such splendid char\nacter that, he soon gained promotion to New England agent then general\neastern agent. From the Pennsylvania Mr. Ripley went to the Burlington,\nserving first as traffic manager and then general manager. From 1890 to\n1895 he was third vice-president of the Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul road\nand In 1896 became president of the Santa Fe, which has steadily improved\nand grown under his guidance.\nSUCCESSOR TO GOV. HUGHES\nWhen Gov. Charles E. Hughes retires in Oc\ntober to become a member of the United States\nSupreme court, Lieutenant Governor White will\nbecome the chief executive of the Empire state.\nLieutenant Governor White is only forty-four\nyears old. His father was Horace K. White, a\nmember of a distinguished Syracuse family. An\ndrew D. White, ex-president of Cornell university\nand former ambassador to Russia and to Ger\nmany, is his uncle. He Is a lawyer by profes\nsion. He bas been active In the Republican party\never since he attained his majority. He has\nfought his party's battles on the stump in nearly\nevery state and national convention for the last\n20 years. In 1898 he was chairman of the Re\npublican state convention which nominated Theo\ndore Roosevelt for governor. White was first elected to the state senate In\n1895 and remained a member of the upper house until bis election as lieu\ntenant governor two years ago.\nHe eats by the clock and sleeps by the clock. According to his friends,\nhe is In deadly fear that pestiferous germs are lying In wait for him and\nbas adopted an elaborate system of safeguards to ward them off.\nBARRETT'S PRAISE OF GIRLS\nJohn Barrett, diplomat, author, one time re\nporter, editor and war correspondent and a great\nbeliever in the future of South America, turned\nhis attention from the affairs of the Latin repub\nlics long enough a few days ago to give anm\nadvice to the fair girl graduates of the land.\nMr. Barrett was speaking to the graduating\nclass of Belcourt seminary in Washington, bul\nhis words could well be taken to heart by every\nyoung woman who Is leaving school this year to\nenter upon her battle of life.\nHe said the women of the world have theli\neyes on the American girl and are watchtnj\nevery step of her progress; they look upon het\nas a model after whom they may pattern with\nprofit He said the young women of this coun\ntry should at all times prove themselves worthy\n1 of this trust whloh the women In the other countries are placing In them.\nThe young woman, he averred, who leaves a Washington seminar\nshould, upon her return home, do her best to exercise her Influence for good\n;upon the community In which she resides. This, It was explained, does nol\nI mean that she should enter politics, but rather that she should do all In\nher power In meeting men who direct affairs to impress upon them theii\nduty to their country, state and city.\nMr. Barrett has been director of the International Bureau of American\nRepublics since 1906 and has never lost an opportunity of talking alioul\nits wcrk and tho food that is to be attained through closer relationshli\ntbe united btatos and the Latin American republic-\nHOW SHE LOOKED AT IT.\nA life-insurance agent was trying\nto Induce young Mr. Nevermuch to\ntake out a policy.\n\"You dwe It to your wife to Insure.\nThen If you die she's provided for.\"\nMrs. Nevermuch was duly Im\npressed and urged her husband to\ncarry some Insurance.\n\"Well, dearie,\" said the hard\npressed man. \"IH explain this propo\nsition to you. Then if you want me\nto take out insurance, I will. It's like\nthis: If I die soon you wilt still be\nIN THE CRISP AND THE GLOW.\nIa th. crisp ud the (low of the mora.\ninc.\nWhen blu. shines the sky overhead.\nWhen the purple and roae of the dawn-\nIns\nArrose the hortton Is spread\nThe Joy! The delight to be living!\nTo feel the red blood In one's velnsl\nMane heart, la transcendant thanks\ngiving.\nGives voice to exuberant trains)\nIa the crisp and the (low of the mora-\ning-\nThe fresh wakened (old at the day\nAll weakness of yeaterday scorning.\nyoung and good-looking enough to cop rJSu ZZm\nout another bread-winner. And If I\nlive long enough the premiums on\nthe Insurance would make the pay\nments on a pianola. Which will you\nnave\nShe decided to take the piano and\nher chances.\nAnother Yarn.\nAnd you were once the tattooed\nman In the circus?\" said the sympa\nthetic housewife.\nYea, mum,\" responded Sandy\nPikes, as he speared a buckwheat\ncake with his fork.\n\"And once you were caught in\nrainstorm and all your colors ran to\ngether? Poor man! Were you out\nof a Job long?\"\nNo, Indeed, mum. Dat very night\nI went around to de melodrama and\ngot a Job as a 'deep dyed villain.'\nStill Invisible.\n\"By the way, old man,\" said the\nchronlo toucher In lubricated tones,\n\"you remember that five-spot I bor\nrowed from you last fall?\"\nies, responded his friend with a\nyawn, \"and every time I think of that\nfive-spot I think of the comet\"\n\"That's a queer combination. What's\nthe similarity?\"\n\"Why, I've been looking for It for\nmonths and haven't seen It yet\"\nHow He Delivered Them.\n\"You want a Job as driver of the\nwagon, ehf said the grocer to the\nraw-looking country youth. \"Yes, sir,\n'Are you one of these fellows that\ncan stand and deliver the goods?\"- \"I\ncan deliver 'em all right, mister, but I\ntlways sit down.\"\nUP TO HIM.\nEdith I told papa that you wanted\nto see him the next time you called.\nEdward What did he say?\nEdith He said all right he wasn't\nafraid of you.\nPerhaps.\n\"Who v.as it said, 'Life Is Just one\nd thing after another?\"\n\"Probably a fellow who saw a\n'snitch' trying to catch a 'blind\ntiger.'\nOf labor for those near and dearl\nHi. breaat of it. mlaery shriving\nIn suiuhine Inspiring and clear.\nIn the glow of the sun's slow retiring\nin. en.p of the slpw twilight's fall\nWith love all his eagerness Bring-\nBweet love for home, wife, child-\nmans all!\nThe joyl The delight! Comnenutlont\nHis soul soars on love-burdened wings!\nno weariness mars the elation\nOf heart-gushing home-songs he sings\nLurana w. Sheldon, In New York\nTimes.\nMISUNDERSTOOD.\nnc:\n13j\nLieutenant (showing party of vlst\ntors over battleship) This Is the\nquarter deck.\nOne of the Party Gee! I thought\nIt was all free!\nVery Seldom.\nYou seldom see a mortal wight.\nNo matter what his labors.\nWho doe.n't find, In fate's despite.\nThe time to knock his neighbors.\nHOW IT HAPPENED.\nThe man who Is always asking fool\nish questions approached the tough\nlooking citizen who was Bitting on the\nsteps of his shanty nursing sore\nhead.\n'What's the matter with your head?\"\nasked Mr. Buttln.\n\"Depression in It,\" was the laconlo\nresponse.\n\"What kind of a depression?\"\n\"Business depression.\"\nnmi mat s a queer place for a\nbusiness depression. How did you\nget it?\"\ni rying to meddle In other peo\nple's business. Now, trot on, stranger.\nbefore you get one of those depres\nsions yourself. They are catching.\"\nAnd Mr. Buttln \"trotted.\"\nJust 8o.\n\"It took me three weeks,\" said the\ntraveling salesman, \"to get an audi\nence with the king. But it was worth\nthe trouble. He conferred a decora\ntion upon me.\"\n\"Booked an order did you?\"\nIllusion 8polled.\n\"I recently made the acquaintance\nof a young woman who declared that\nshe had never wanted to go on the\nstage.\"\n\"Most sensible.\"\n\"1 wag on the point of so consider\ning her when she Informed me that\nshe hoped some day to fly with Paul-ban.\"\nContradictory Aspect.\n\"I have found out that Gadsby Is\nleading a double life.\" \"That's singular.\"\nContrary.\n\"I dreamed last night that I pro\nposed to you and you accepted me.\"\n\"Dreams go by contraries, you\nknow.\"\n\"I know, and I am not going to pro\npose and you are not going to accept\nme.\"\nA Little Touch.\nBacker How did the Bhow go?\nManager It went like a breeze.\nBacker I thought It would ta'te\nsomething like a draft or so to nuke\nIt go.\nThe Professor.\nHis hair la long.\nHe plays quite well\nAnd has a name\nLike a college yell.\nThe Producer.\n\"It must be annoying to have to ask\nyour husband for money,\" said the In\ntrusive woman.\n\"I wouldn't think of doing so,\" re\nplied Mrs. Cumrox. \"We Insist on\nfamily games of bridge, and In that\nway avoid being under the slightest\nobligations for what he contributes.\"\nThe Girls.\nMayme When I take my hair down\nit comes below my knees.\nGrayce Why did you buy a length\nthat doesn't fit you? 1\nThe Main Place,\n\"Lieutenant Shackleton says he Is\ndetermined the British flag shall float\nover1 the Antarctic pole.\" \"Well, the\nBritish are noted for going to the bot\ntom of things, but what does that mat\nter so long as we are at the top?\"\nPleases Him.\n\"Scribbles .writes some very pleas\nlog verse.\"\n\"Indeed? I've never heard of Its\npleasing anybody.\"\n\"Evidently you've never observed\nits effect on Scribbles,\"\nBy ELEANOR LEXINGTON\nCampbell Family\n(Copyright by McClure Syndicate)\nIn the Highlands particular names\nare associated with certain localities,\nso that one cannot well think of the\nname Campbell without associating It\nwith Argyllshire, as the name of Gor\ndon Is connected with the Spey val\nley and Mackenzie with Rpss-shlre.\nThe family name of the earls of Ar\ngyll Is Campbell. Colin Campbell,\nnephew of Sir Colin Campbell, who\nmarried a daughter of Lord Lorn, was\ncreated first earl of Argyll In 1457. by\nJames II. He was master of the king's\nhousehold and held the highest offices\nIn the kingdom.\nThe Clan Campbell places Constan\ntine of France, A. D. 404, upon the top\nmost bough of their family tree. This\ntakes In Ambrose, the forty-third king\nof the Scots, and another king who\nwas the sixty-ninth, and best and most\nromantic of all, Arthur of the round\ntable.\nOf this line Diarmld MacDulbhne\nmarried Grain, niece of the great\nO'Nell of Ireland. Their son Malcolm\nwent to Normandy and married the\nheiress of Beauchamp, niece of Wil\nliam the Conqueror. From Beauchamp\n(French) to De Bello campo (Latin)\n\"beautiful field\" and to Campbell is\nbut a step and the clan O'Dulbhne, In\nArgyllshire assumed the name Camp\nbell. However, we are on the wrong\ntrack, some authorities would assure\nus, upon their honor. We will begin\nthen with Campbell as a Gaelic word,\nmeaning nothing more romantic than\ncrooked mouth,\" from cam or kam,\ntrooked, and bell mouth. By the same\nreasoning Cameron means crooked\nnose.\nWe need not stop here. There Is\nthe old Norse word kappl or kempa,\nthe Anglo-Saxon caempa or cempa;\nthe old German kampe or kampfer,\nall meaning champion, and anyone of\nthese with \"ell\" or \"el\" (little) gives\nus \"the little champion.\"\nThe tenth knight of Lochore, Ar\ngyllshire, and a Campbell, was Neil\nMffiallen More, one of the worthies of\nRobert the Bruce. It was he, or one\nof the M'Cailen Mores, who killed the\nbiggest boar in the country by cut\nting off Its head with one stroke.\nHence the boar's head of the coat of\narms.\nOne immigrant forefather was John,\nson of Lord Nell Campbell. He set\ntled in New Jersey, 1684. The Camp\nbells of early Virginia days were pro\ngenitors of the southern and western\nbranches.\nRev. Archibald and his brother Al\nexander were Virginia pioneers. The\nformer had charge of, a church in\nWashington pariBh, Westmoreland\ncounty, Va. He also kept a school and\nWashington, the Lees, Marshalls, Mad\nIsons and Monroes may have been\namong his pupils, between 1754 and\n1774, as their families were members\nof his church. Alexander lived at Fal\nmouth, but when the revolution broke\nout, taking sides with the British, he\nreturned to Scotland. His youngest\nson, born at Glasgow, 1777, waa the\npoet Thomas, whose brother married\na daughter of Patrick Henry.\nRev. Archibald's second wife was a\nsister of Rev. William Stuart, of King\nGeorge county, and they had three\nsons. One son, Alexander, was Unit\ned States attorney for Virginia, re\nceiving his appointment from Washington,.\nIn South Carolina there nav bn\nCampbells since time was and ;&r\nrlage relations include the Lewises,\nthe Taliaferros and the Simm\"ui, or\nSlmocs. Thomas la always a fortt\nname.\nOne New England father was John\nCampbell of Argyllshire. He .waa\npostmaster of Boston, was the editor\nand proprietor of the Newt Letter,\nwhich made Its first appearance April\n24, 1704, and was one of the first jour\nnals published here. In 1719 he en\nlarged It, \"to make the news newer and\nmore acceptable, whereby that which\nseemed old In the former half sheet\nbecomes new now by the sheet This\ntime a year ago we were 13 month\nbehind In foreign news.\" He en\ncourages bit subscribers with the as\nsurance that \"if they will continue\nsteady until January next, life permit\nting, they will be accommodated with\nall the news of Europe, that Is need\nful to be known\" \"all the news thata\nfit to print\"\nJohn Campbell, 1717, was an Oxford.\nMass., settler.\nRobert Campbell, born 1J73, In Ire\nland, wag living at New London.\nConn.. 1719, with his wife Janet They\nhad six children, and two, Charles and\nJohn, were members of the church of\nVoluntown, Conn. Some members of\nthis line were founders of the New\nYork family of Campbells, and mar\nriage relation include the Palmer.\nTerrys, Wylles. Houstons and Klnneav,\nLieut. James Campbell, grandson\nRobert, the pilgrim, waa born' 11\nand died 1812. He was member\nthe Connecticut militia. He marri\nDinah McMain, and they had 13 cl\ndren.\nAmong revolutionary soldiers, t\nfollowing are named: From Mast\nchusetts, Capt William Campbei\nConnecticut, Lieut, Moses; New Yol\nCol. Donald, Lieut Duncan and Ensif\nJames; New Jersey, Surgeon Johl\nDelaware, Ensign James; Pennar\nvania, Lleuts. William, Archibald, R\nert and James; Maryland, Capt. Ens\nand Lieut James; Virginia, Caf\nWilliam, John and Richard, and L\nArchibald; North Carolina, LI(.\nJohn and James. Capt Whltaker\nCampbell, born in King .and Queen\ncounty, Virginia, where be died( 1814,\nwas a \"boy of '76.\"\nCol. Samuel Campbell, of the conti\nnental army, was born In New Hamp\nshire, but lived In New York state.\nThe original of \"Highland Mary.\"\nwas Mary Campbell, a bonnie lassie,\nand to her Burns wrote the lines \"Will\nye Go to the Indies, My Mao It\nwas her memory which Inspired\npathetic lines, \"To Mary In Heaven.\"\nThomas Campbell's \"Pleasures of\nHope,\" is called the finest didactic\npoem In the English language a poem\nwnicn published, when he was 22\nyears old, brought him Immediate)\nfame, If not fortune.\nThe Campbells have been heroes\nupon many a field, and their prowess\nhas inspired many a pen. Rob Roy,\nthat popular Highland hero, (we men\ntion only in parenthesis, that he waa\na highwayman), had Campbell blood.\nThe coat-of-arms shown Is blazoned:\nquarterly; first and fourth, gyronny\noi eigni, or ana sable, (for Campbell)\nsecond and third, argent, a lymphad,\nsails furled and oars In action, all\nsable, flags and pennants flying, gules,\n(for Lorn).\nCrest: A boar's head, couped, or,\nover crest the legend, Ne Obllvlscarls.\nMotto: Vix Ea Nostro Voce I\nscarce call these deeds of our ances\ntors ours. This Is also the motto ot\nthe Greville and Fountalne families.\nThe supporters of this coat-armor,\nare two lions guardant gules.\nThe Campbells of New Jersey and\nGeorgia bear this coat-of-arms, the\none ascribed to John Campbell of Boa\nton 1696, Is: Gyronny of eight, sable\nand or, a bordure of the second,\ncharged with eight crescents of the\nfirst; a martlet, sable, on the detxer\ngyron, or, for difference.. f\nCrest: Two oars of a galley U.\nsaltire, proper.\nMotto: By Sea and Land.\nThe motto, Ne Obliviscarls you? f\nmust not forget Is the motto for j\nLorn. It Is also that of the M'Tavlsh,\nand Colvll or Colville families.\nForty arms, more or less, are given\nin \"Burke's Peerage\" for the Camp\nbells.\nChalk Bread and Cereal Meats, j\n\"One doesn't see so much counterA\"\nfelt money nowadays.\"\n\"No. Money Is so cheap and food ak\nhigh that the talent Is counterfeiting\nfood Instead.\"\nA girl likes an honest young man\nif he Isn't too honest to steal a kiss.\nThe woman who tells everything she\nhears generally adds a little bit more.\nif-\nA\nf","height":"25216","width":"16340"}}
